{"id":"1807.09106","submitter":"Benjamin Wiener","authors":"Benjamin Wiener and Derek Stein","title":"Electrokinetic Current Driven by a Viscosity Gradient","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Gradients of voltage, pressure, temperature, and salinity can transport\nobjects in micro- and nanofluidic systems by well known mechanisms. Here we\nreport the discovery of a transport effect driven by viscosity gradients, which\ncause an ionic current to flow inside a glass nanofluidic channel. Measurements\nof the current are well described by a simple model wherein counterions in the\nelectric double layers near the surfaces drift in the direction of decreasing\nviscosity with a drift speed equal to the gradient of the ions' local\ndiffusivity. Drift in a viscosity gradient is a consequence of multiplicative\n(state-dependent) noise, which results from a particle's thermal fluctuations\ndepending on its position. This surprisingly large effect, measured in a highly\ncontrolled nanofluidic environment, reveals fundamental behavior that is\nrelevant to a broad range of systems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 23 Jul 2018 13:59:10 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 26 Jul 2018 16:14:00 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 16 Nov 2018 20:39:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-11-20"}
{"id":"1807.09115","submitter":"W. M. Stuckey","authors":"W.M. Stuckey, Michael Silberstein, Timothy McDevitt, and Ian Kohler","title":"Why the Tsirelson Bound? Bub's Question and Fuchs' Desideratum","comments":"Contains corrections to the published version","journal-ref":"Entropy 2019, 21, 692; doi:10.3390/e21070692","doi":"10.3390/e21070692","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  To answer Wheeler's question \"Why the quantum?\" via quantum information\ntheory according to Bub, one must explain both why the world is quantum rather\nthan classical and why the world is quantum rather than superquantum, i.e.,\n\"Why the Tsirelson bound?\" We show that the quantum correlations and quantum\nstates corresponding to the Bell basis states, which uniquely produce the\nTsirelson bound for the Clauser-Horne-Shimony-Holt quantity, can be derived\nfrom conservation per no preferred reference frame (NPRF). A reference frame in\nthis context is defined by a measurement configuration, just as with the light\npostulate of special relativity. We therefore argue that the Tsirelson bound is\nultimately based on NPRF just as the postulates of special relativity. This\nconstraint-based/principle answer to Bub's question addresses Fuchs'\ndesideratum that we \"take the structure of quantum theory and change it from\nthis very overt mathematical speak ... into something like [special\nrelativity].\" Thus, the answer to Bub's question per Fuchs' desideratum is,\n\"the Tsirelson bound obtains due to conservation per NPRF.\"\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 23 Jul 2018 13:28:57 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 9 Aug 2018 17:08:56 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 24 Aug 2018 15:28:21 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 9 Oct 2018 16:38:31 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Mon, 27 May 2019 16:06:09 GMT"},{"version":"v6","created":"Wed, 17 Jul 2019 14:08:32 GMT"},{"version":"v7","created":"